# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: csrf-protection
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In computing, **cross-origin resource sharing** (**CORS**) is a mechanism to safely bypass the same-origin policy; that is, it allows a web page to access restricted resources from a web server on a domain name different from the domain that served the web page.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A web page may freely embed cross-origin images, stylesheets, scripts, iframes, and videos.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Certain "cross-domain" HTTP requests, notably Ajax requests, are forbidden by default by the same-origin security policy.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] CORS defines a way in which a web browser and server can interact to determine whether it is safe to allow the cross-origin request.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] It allows for more freedom and functionality than purely same-origin requests, but is more secure than simply allowing all cross-origin requests.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The specification for CORS is included as part of the WHATWG's Fetch Living Standard.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] This specification describes how CORS is currently implemented in browsers.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] An earlier specification was published as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Servers can also notify clients whether "credentials" (including Cookies and HTTP Authentication data) should be sent with requests.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Suppose a user visits http://www.example.com and the page attempts a cross-origin request to fetch data from http://service.example.com.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A CORS-compatible browser will attempt to make a cross-origin request to service.example.com as follows.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A wildcard same-origin policy is appropriate when a page or API response is intended to be accessible to any code on any site.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A freely available web font on a public hosting service like Google Fonts is an example.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The value of "*" is special in that it does not allow requests to supply credentials, meaning that it does not allow HTTP authentication, client-side SSL certificates, or cookies to be sent in the cross-domain request.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Note that in the CORS architecture, the Access-Control-Allow-Origin header is being set by the external web service (*service.example.com*), not the original web application server (*www.example.com*).
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Here, *service.example.com* uses CORS to permit the browser to authorize *www.example.com* to make requests to *service.example.com*.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] If a site specifies the header "Access-Control-Allow-Credentials:true", third-party sites may be able to carry out privileged actions and retrieve sensitive information.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] When performing certain types of cross-domain Ajax requests, modern browsers that support CORS will initiate an extra "preflight" request to determine whether they have permission to perform the action.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Cross-origin requests are preflighted this way because they may have implications to user data.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The browser will then make the actual request.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] If service.example.com does not accept cross-site requests from this origin then it will respond with error to the OPTIONS request and the browser will not make the actual request.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Cross-origin support was originally proposed by Matt Oshry, Brad Porter, and Michael Bodell of Tellme Networks in March 2004 for inclusion in VoiceXML 2.1 to allow safe cross-origin data requests by VoiceXML browsers.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The mechanism was deemed general in nature and not specific to VoiceXML and was subsequently separated into an implementation NOTE.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The WebApps Working Group of the W3C with participation from the major browser vendors began to formalize the NOTE into a W3C Working Draft on track toward formal W3C Recommendation status.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In May 2006 the first W3C Working Draft was submitted.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In March 2009 the draft was renamed to "Cross-Origin Resource Sharing" and in January 2014 it was accepted as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The main advantage of JSONP was its ability to work on legacy browsers which predate CORS support (Opera Mini and Internet Explorer 9 and earlier).
[src:csrf-protection/cross-origin-resource-sharing] CORS is now supported by most modern web browsers, and can be used as a modern alternative to the JSONP pattern.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The term "CSRF" is also used as an abbreviation in defences against CSRF attacks, such as techniques that use header data, form data, or cookies, to test for and prevent such attacks.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] In a CSRF attack, the attacker's goal is to cause an innocent victim to unknowingly submit a maliciously crafted web request to a website that the victim has privileged access to.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] This web request can be crafted to include URL parameters, cookies and other data that appear normal to the web server processing the request.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] At risk are web applications that perform actions based on input from trusted and authenticated users without requiring the user to authorize (e.g. via a popup confirmation) the specific action.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] A user who is authenticated by a cookie saved in the user's web browser could unknowingly send an HTTP request to a site that trusts the user and thereby cause an unwanted action.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] A general property of web browsers is that they will automatically and invisibly include any cookies (including session cookies and others) used by a given domain in any web request sent to that domain.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] This property is exploited by CSRF attacks.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] In order for a CSRF attack to work, an attacker must identify a reproducible web request that executes a specific action such as changing an account password on the target page.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Once such a request is identified, a link can be created that generates this malicious request and that link can be embedded on a page within the attacker's control.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] This link may be placed in such a way that it is not even necessary for the victim to click the link.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] For example, it may be embedded within an html image tag on an email sent to the victim which will automatically be loaded when the victim opens their email.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Once the victim has clicked the link, their browser will automatically include any cookies used by that website and submit the request to the web server.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The web server will not be able to identify the forgery because the request was made by a user that was logged in, and submitted all the requisite cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Cross-site request forgery is an example of a confused deputy attack against a web browser because the web browser is tricked into submitting a forged request by a less privileged attacker.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] CSRF Token vulnerabilities have been known and in some cases exploited since 2001.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Because it is carried out from the user's IP address, some website logs might not have evidence of CSRF.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Attackers who can find a reproducible link that executes a specific action on the target page while the victim is logged in can embed such link on a page they control and trick the victim into opening it.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The attack carrier link may be placed in a location that the victim is likely to visit while logged into the target site (for example, a discussion forum), or sent in an HTML email body or attachment.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Attacks were launched by placing malicious, automatic-action HTML image elements on forums and email spam, so that browsers visiting these pages would open them automatically, without much user action.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] People running vulnerable μTorrent version at the same time as opening these pages were susceptible to the attack.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] When accessing the attack link to the local μTorrent application at localhost:8080, the browser would also always automatically send any existing cookies for that domain.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] This general property of web browsers enables CSRF attacks to exploit their targeted vulnerabilities and execute hostile actions as long as the user is logged into the target website (in this example, the local μTorrent web interface) at the time of the attack.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Because of this assumption, many existing CSRF prevention mechanisms in web frameworks will **not** cover GET requests, but rather apply the protection only to HTTP methods that are intended to be state-changing.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] An attacker may forge a request to log the victim into a target website using the attacker's credentials; this is known as *login CSRF*.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Login CSRF makes various novel attacks possible; for instance, an attacker can later log into the site with their legitimate credentials and view private information like activity history that has been saved in the account.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] This attack has been demonstrated against Google and Yahoo.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Depending on the type, the HTTP request methods vary in their susceptibility to the CSRF attacks (due to the differences in their handling by the web browsers).
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Therefore, the protective measures against an attack depend on the method of the HTTP request.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] CSRF tokens could also be sent to a client by an attacker due to session fixation or other vulnerabilities, or guessed via a brute-force attack, rendered on a malicious page that generates thousands of failed requests.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The attack class of "Dynamic CSRF", or using a per-client payload for session-specific forgery, was described in 2009 by Nathan Hamiel and Shawn Moyer at the BlackHat Briefings, though the taxonomy has yet to gain wider adoption.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] A new vector for composing dynamic CSRF attacks was presented by Oren Ofer at a local OWASP chapter meeting in January 2012 – "AJAX Hammer – Dynamic CSRF".
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Severity metrics have been issued for CSRF token vulnerabilities that result in remote code execution with root privileges as well as a vulnerability that can compromise a root certificate, which will completely undermine a public key infrastructure.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The attacker must find a state-changing action at the target site, such as a form submission or a URL that does something (e.g., transfers money, or changes the victim's e-mail address or password).
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Actions that only retrieve data are not useful as CSRF targets, because the attacker does not receive the response.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The attacker must determine the right values for all the forms or URL inputs; if any of them are required to be secret authentication values or IDs that the attacker can't guess, the attack will fail.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The attacker must lure the victim to a web page with malicious code while the victim is logged into the target site.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The victim has to be authenticated in a way that is automatically included in browser requests, such as a session cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] This enables authentication to be included in the attacker's malicious requests.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The attack is blind: the attacker cannot see what the target website sends back to the victim in response to the forged requests, unless they exploit a cross-site scripting vulnerability or other bug at the target website.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Similarly, the attacker can only target any links or submit any forms that come up after the initial forged request if those subsequent links or forms are similarly predictable.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Multiple targets can be simulated by including multiple images on a page, or by using JavaScript to introduce a delay between clicks.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Most CSRF prevention techniques work by embedding additional authentication data into requests that allows the web application to detect requests from unauthorized locations.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Synchronizer token pattern (STP) is a technique where a token, a secret and unique value for each request, is embedded by the web application in all HTML forms and verified on the server side.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The token may be generated by any method that ensures unpredictability and uniqueness (e.g. using a hash chain of random seed).
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] This is called an anti-forgery token in ASP.NET.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The attacker is thus unable to place a correct token in their requests to authenticate them.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] STP is the most compatible as it only relies on HTML, but introduces some complexity on the server side, due to the burden associated with checking validity of the token on each request.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] As the token is unique and unpredictable, it also enforces proper sequence of events (e.g. screen 1, then 2, then 3) which raises usability problem (e.g. user opens multiple tabs).
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] It can be relaxed by using per session CSRF token instead of per request CSRF token.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Security of this technique is based on the assumption that only JavaScript running on the client side of an HTTPS connection to the server that initially set the cookie will be able to read the cookie's value.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] JavaScript running from a rogue file or email should not be able to successfully read the cookie value to copy into the custom header.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Even though the csrf-token **cookie** may be automatically sent with the rogue request, subject to the cookies SameSite policy, the server will still expect a valid X-Csrf-Token **header**.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The CSRF token itself should be unique and unpredictable.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The CSRF token cookie must not have httpOnly flag, as it is intended to be read by JavaScript by design.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] This technique is implemented by many modern frameworks, such as Django and AngularJS.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Because the token remains constant over the whole user session, it works well with AJAX applications, but does not enforce sequence of events in the web application.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Similarly to the cookie-to-header approach, but without involving JavaScript, a site can set a CSRF token as a cookie, and also insert it as a hidden field in each HTML form.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] When the form is submitted, the site can check that the cookie token matches the form token.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The same-origin policy prevents an attacker from reading or setting cookies on the target domain, so they cannot put a valid token in their crafted form.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The advantage of this technique over the Synchronizer pattern is that the token does not need to be stored on the server.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] However, if the site in question has cookie setting functionality, this protection can be bypassed.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] An additional "SameSite" attribute can be included when the server sets a cookie, instructing the browser on whether to attach the cookie to cross-site requests.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] If this attribute is set to "strict", then the cookie will only be sent on same-site requests, making CSRF ineffective.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] However, this requires the browser to recognise and correctly implement the attribute.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Browser extensions such as RequestPolicy (for Mozilla Firefox) or uMatrix (for both Firefox and Google Chrome/Chromium) can prevent CSRF by providing a default-deny policy for cross-site requests.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] However, this can significantly interfere with the normal operation of many websites.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The CsFire extension (also for Firefox) can mitigate the impact of CSRF with less impact on normal browsing, by removing authentication information from cross-site requests.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The NoScript extension for Firefox mitigates CSRF threats by distinguishing trusted from untrusted sites, and removing authentication & payloads from POST requests sent by untrusted sites to trusted ones.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The Application Boundary Enforcer module in NoScript also blocks requests sent from internet pages to local sites (e.g. localhost), preventing CSRF attacks on local services (such as uTorrent) or routers.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] The Self Destructing Cookies extension for Firefox does not directly protect from CSRF, but can reduce the attack window, by deleting cookies as soon as they are no longer associated with an open tab.
[src:csrf-protection/cross-site-request-forgery] Cross-site scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities (even in other applications running on the same domain) allow attackers to bypass essentially all CSRF preventions.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] An **HTTP cookie** (also called **web cookie**, **Internet cookie**, **browser cookie**, or simply **cookie**) is a small block of data created by a web server while a user is browsing a website and placed on the user's computer or other device by the user's web browser.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are placed on the device used to access a website, and more than one cookie may be placed on a user's device during a session.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies serve useful and sometimes essential functions on the web.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] They enable web servers to store stateful information (such as items added in the shopping cart in an online store) on the user's device or to track the user's browsing activity (including clicking particular buttons, logging in, or recording which pages were visited in the past).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] They can also be used to save information that the user previously entered into form fields, such as names, addresses, passwords, and payment card numbers for subsequent use.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie* was coined by web-browser programmer Lou Montulli.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] It was derived from the term *magic cookie*, which is a packet of data a program receives and sends back unchanged, used by Unix programmers.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Magic cookies were already used in computing when computer programmer Lou Montulli had the idea of using them in web communications in June 1994.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] At the time, he was an employee of Netscape Communications, which was developing an e-commerce application for MCI.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Vint Cerf and John Klensin represented MCI in technical discussions with Netscape Communications.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] MCI did not want its servers to have to retain partial transaction states, which led them to ask Netscape to find a way to store that state in each user's computer instead.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies provided a solution to the problem of reliably implementing a virtual shopping cart.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Together with John Giannandrea, Montulli wrote the initial Netscape cookie specification the same year.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Version 0.9beta of Mosaic Netscape, released on 13 October 1994, supported cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The first use of cookies (out of the labs) was checking whether visitors to the Netscape website had already visited the site.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Montulli applied for a patent for the cookie technology in 1995, which was granted in 1998.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Support for cookies was integrated with Internet Explorer in version 2, released in October 1995.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The introduction of cookies was not widely known to the public at the time.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In particular, cookies were accepted by default, and users were not notified of their presence.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The public learned about cookies after the *Financial Times* published an article about them on 12 February 1996.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In the same year, cookies received a lot of media attention, especially because of potential privacy implications.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Federal Trade Commission hearings in 1996 and 1997.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The development of the formal cookie specifications was already ongoing.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In particular, the first discussions about a formal specification started in April 1995 on the www-talk mailing list.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A special working group within the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) was formed.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Two alternative proposals for introducing state in HTTP transactions had been proposed by Brian Behlendorf and David Kristol respectively.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] But the group, headed by Kristol himself and Lou Montulli, soon decided to use the Netscape specification as a starting point.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In February 1996, the working group identified third-party cookies as a considerable privacy threat.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The specification produced by the group was eventually published as RFC 2109 in February 1997.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] It specifies that third-party cookies were either not allowed at all, or at least not enabled by default.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] At this time, advertising companies were already using third-party cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The recommendation about third-party cookies of RFC 2109 was not followed by Netscape and Internet Explorer.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2109 was superseded by RFC 2965 in October 2000.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2965 added a `Set-Cookie2` header field, which informally came to be called "RFC 2965-style cookies" as opposed to the original `Set-Cookie` header field which was called "Netscape-style cookies".
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] `Set-Cookie2` was seldom used, however, and was deprecated in RFC 6265 in April 2011 which was written as a definitive specification for cookies as used in the real world.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] No modern browser recognizes the `Set-Cookie2` header field.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A *session cookie* (also known as an *in-memory cookie*, *transient cookie* or *non-persistent cookie*) exists only in temporary memory while the user navigates a website.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies expire or are deleted when the user closes the web browser.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are identified by the browser by the absence of an expiration date assigned to them.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A *persistent cookie* expires at a specific date or after a specific length of time.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For the persistent cookie's lifespan set by its creator, its information will be transmitted to the server every time the user visits the website that it belongs to, or every time the user views a resource belonging to that website from another website (such as an advertisement).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, persistent cookies are sometimes referred to as *tracking cookies* because they can be used by advertisers to record information about a user's web browsing habits over an extended period of time.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Persistent cookies are also used for reasons such as keeping users logged into their accounts on websites, to avoid re-entering login credentials at every visit.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A *secure cookie* can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection (i.e.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] They cannot be transmitted over unencrypted connections (i.e.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This makes the cookie less likely to be exposed to cookie theft via eavesdropping.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is made secure by adding the `Secure` flag to the cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] An *http-only cookie* cannot be accessed by client-side APIs, such as JavaScript.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This restriction eliminates the threat of cookie theft via cross-site scripting (XSS).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] However, the cookie remains vulnerable to cross-site tracing (XST) and cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is given this characteristic by adding the `HttpOnly` flag to the cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In 2016 Google Chrome version 51 introduced a new kind of cookie with attribute `SameSite` with possible values of `Strict`, `Lax` or `None`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] With attribute `SameSite=Strict`, the browsers would only send cookies to a target domain that is the same as the origin domain.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This would effectively mitigate cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] With `SameSite=Lax`, browsers would send cookies with requests to a target domain even it is different from the origin domain, but only for *safe* requests such as GET (POST is unsafe) and not third-party cookies (inside iframe).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Attribute `SameSite=None` would allow third-party (cross-site) cookies, however, most browsers require secure attribute on SameSite=None cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The Same-site cookie is incorporated into a new RFC draft for "Cookies: HTTP State Management Mechanism" to update RFC 6265 (if approved).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Chrome, Firefox, and Edge started to support Same-site cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The key of rollout is the treatment of existing cookies without the SameSite attribute defined, Chrome has been treating those existing cookies as if SameSite=None, this would let all website/applications run as before.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Google intended to change that default to `SameSite=Lax` in Chrome 80 planned to be released in February 2020, but due to potential for breakage of those applications/websites that rely on third-party/cross-site cookies and COVID-19 circumstances, Google postponed this change to Chrome 84.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A *supercookie* is a cookie with an origin of a top-level domain (such as `.com`) or a public suffix (such as `.co.uk`).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Ordinary cookies, by contrast, have an origin of a specific domain name, such as `example.com`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Supercookies can be a potential security concern and are therefore often blocked by web browsers.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] If unblocked by the browser, an attacker in control of a malicious website could set a supercookie and potentially disrupt or impersonate legitimate user requests to another website that shares the same top-level domain or public suffix as the malicious website.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For example, a supercookie with an origin of `.com` could maliciously affect a request made to `example.com`, even if the cookie did not originate from `example.com`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This can be used to fake logins or change user information.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List helps to mitigate the risk that supercookies pose.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List is a cross-vendor initiative that aims to provide an accurate and up-to-date list of domain name suffixes.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Older versions of browsers may not have an up-to-date list, and will therefore be vulnerable to supercookies from certain domains.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The term *supercookie* is also used for tracking technologies that do not rely on HTTP cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Two such *supercookie* mechanisms were found on Microsoft websites in August 2011: cookie syncing that respawned MUID (machine unique identifier) cookies, and ETag cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Due to media attention, Microsoft later disabled this code.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In a 2021 blog post, Mozilla used the term *supercookie* to refer to the use of browser cache as a means of tracking users across sites.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Zero or more attributes (name/value pairs).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Attributes store information such as the cookie's expiration, domain, and flags (such as `Secure` and `HttpOnly`).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies were originally introduced to provide a way for users to record items they want to purchase as they navigate throughout a website (a virtual *shopping cart* or *shopping basket*).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Today, however, the contents of a user's shopping cart are usually stored in a database on the server, rather than in a cookie on the client.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] To keep track of which user is assigned to which shopping cart, the server sends a cookie to the client that contains a unique session identifier (typically, a long string of random letters and numbers).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Because cookies are sent to the server with every request the client makes, that session identifier will be sent back to the server every time the user visits a new page on the website, which lets the server know which shopping cart to display to the user.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Another popular use of cookies is for logging into websites.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] When the user visits a website's login page, the web server typically sends the client a cookie containing a unique session identifier.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] When the user successfully logs in, the server remembers that that particular session identifier has been authenticated and grants the user access to its services.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Because session cookies only contain a unique session identifier, this makes the amount of personal information that a website can save about each user virtually limitless—the website is not limited to restrictions concerning how large a cookie can be.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies also help to improve page load times, since the amount of information in a session cookie is small and requires little bandwidth.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can be used to remember information about the user in order to show relevant content to that user over time.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For example, a web server might send a cookie containing the username that was last used to log into a website, so that it may be filled in automatically the next time the user logs in.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Many websites use cookies for personalization based on the user's preferences.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Users select their preferences by entering them in a web form and submitting the form to the server.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The server encodes the preferences in a cookie and sends the cookie back to the browser.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This way, every time the user accesses a page on the website, the server can personalize the page according to the user's preferences.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For example, the Google search engine once used cookies to allow users (even non-registered ones) to decide how many search results per page they wanted to see.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Also, DuckDuckGo uses cookies to allow users to set the viewing preferences like colors of the web page.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Tracking cookies are used to track users' web browsing habits.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This can also be done to some extent by using the IP address of the computer requesting the page or the referer field of the HTTP request header, but cookies allow for greater precision.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] From this point on, the cookie will automatically be sent by the browser to the server every time a new page from the site is requested.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The server not only sends the page as usual but also stores the URL of the requested page, the date/time of the request, and the cookie in a log file.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] By analyzing this log file, it is then possible to discover which pages the user has visited, in what sequence, and for how long.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Corporations exploit users' web habits by tracking cookies to collect information about buying habits.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The *Wall Street Journal* found that America's top fifty websites installed an average of sixty-four pieces of tracking technology onto computers, resulting in a total of 3,180 tracking files.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The data can then be collected and sold to bidding corporations.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are arbitrary pieces of data, usually chosen and first sent by the web server, and stored on the client computer by the web browser.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The browser then sends them back to the server with every request, introducing states (memory of previous events) into otherwise stateless HTTP transactions.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Without cookies, each retrieval of a web page or component of a web page would be an isolated event, largely unrelated to all other page views made by the user on the website.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Although cookies are usually set by the web server, they can also be set by the client using a scripting language such as JavaScript (unless the cookie's `HttpOnly` flag is set, in which case the cookie cannot be modified by scripting languages).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are set using the `Set-Cookie` header field, sent in an HTTP response from the web server.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This header field instructs the web browser to store the cookie and send it back in future requests to the server (the browser will ignore this header field if it does not support cookies or has disabled cookies).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The server's HTTP response contains the contents of the website's homepage.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] But it also instructs the browser to set two cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The first, *theme*, is considered to be a *session cookie* since it does not have an `Expires` or `Max-Age` attribute.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are intended to be deleted by the browser when the browser closes.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The second, *sessionToken*, is considered to be a *persistent cookie* since it contains an `Expires` attribute, which instructs the browser to delete the cookie at a specific date and time.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Next, the browser sends another request to visit the `spec.html` page on the website.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This way, the server knows that this HTTP request is related to the previous one.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The server would answer by sending the requested page, possibly including more `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response in order to instruct the browser to add new cookies, modify existing cookies, or remove existing cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] To remove a cookie, the server must include a `Set-Cookie` header field with an expiration date in the past.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The value of a cookie may consist of any printable ASCII character (`!` through `~`, Unicode `\u0021` through `\u007E`) excluding `,`and`;` and whitespace characters.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The name of a cookie excludes the same characters, as well as `=`, since that is the delimiter between the name and value.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The cookie standard RFC 2965 is more restrictive but not implemented by browsers.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie crumb* is sometimes used to refer to a cookie's name–value pair.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be set by scripting languages such as JavaScript that run within the browser.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In JavaScript, the object `document.cookie` is used for this purpose.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For example, the instruction `document.cookie = "temperature=20"` creates a cookie of name *temperature* and value *20*.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In addition to a name and value, cookies can also have one or more attributes.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Browsers do not include cookie attributes in requests to the server—they only send the cookie's name and value.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookie attributes are used by browsers to determine when to delete a cookie, block a cookie or whether to send a cookie to the server.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The `Domain` and `Path` attributes define the scope of the cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] They essentially tell the browser what website the cookie belongs to.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For security reasons, cookies can only be set on the current resource's top domain and its subdomains, and not for another domain and its subdomains.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For example, the website `example.org` cannot set a cookie that has a domain of `foo.com` because this would allow the website `example.org` to control the cookies of the domain `foo.com`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] If a cookie's `Domain` and `Path` attributes are not specified by the server, they default to the domain and path of the resource that was requested.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] However, in most browsers there is a difference between a cookie set from `foo.com` without a domain, and a cookie set with the `foo.com` domain.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In the former case, the cookie will only be sent for requests to `foo.com`, also known as a host-only cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In the latter case, all subdomains are also included (for example, `docs.foo.com`).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A notable exception to this general rule is Edge prior to Windows 10 RS3 and Internet Explorer prior to IE 11 and Windows 10 RS4 (April 2018), which always sends cookies to subdomains regardless of whether the cookie was set with or without a domain.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Below is an example of some `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response of a website after a user logged in.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `LSID`, has no `Domain` attribute, and has a `Path` attribute set to `/accounts`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This tells the browser to use the cookie only when requesting pages contained in `docs.foo.com/accounts` (the domain is derived from the request domain).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The other two cookies, `HSID` and `SSID`, would be used when the browser requests any subdomain in `.foo.com` on any path (for example `www.foo.com/bar`).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The prepending dot is optional in recent standards, but can be added for compatibility with RFC 2109 based implementations.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The `Expires` attribute defines a specific date and time for when the browser should delete the cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The date and time are specified in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YYYY HH:MM:SS GMT`, or in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YY HH:MM:SS GMT` for values of YY where YY is greater than or equal to 0 and less than or equal to 69.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Alternatively, the `Max-Age` attribute can be used to set the cookie's expiration as an interval of seconds in the future, relative to the time the browser received the cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `lu`, is set to expire sometime on 15 January 2013.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] It will be used by the client browser until that time.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The second cookie, `made_write_conn`, does not have an expiration date, making it a session cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] It will be deleted after the user closes their browser.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The third cookie, `reg_fb_gate`, has its value changed to *deleted*, with an expiration time in the past.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The browser will delete this cookie right away because its expiration time is in the past.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Note that cookie will only be deleted if the domain and path attributes in the `Set-Cookie` field match the values used when the cookie was created.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] As of 2016 Internet Explorer did not support `Max-Age`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` and `HttpOnly` attributes do not have associated values.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Rather, the presence of just their attribute names indicates that their behaviors should be enabled.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` attribute is meant to keep cookie communication limited to encrypted transmission, directing browsers to use cookies only via secure/encrypted connections.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] However, if a web server sets a cookie with a secure attribute from a non-secure connection, the cookie can still be intercepted when it is sent to the user by man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Therefore, for maximum security, cookies with the Secure attribute should only be set over a secure connection.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The `HttpOnly` attribute directs browsers not to expose cookies through channels other than HTTP (and HTTPS) requests.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This means that the cookie cannot be accessed via client-side scripting languages (notably JavaScript), and therefore cannot be stolen easily via cross-site scripting (a pervasive attack technique).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Most modern browsers support cookies and allow the user to disable them.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Add-on tools for managing cookie permissions also exist.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies have some important implications for the privacy and anonymity of web users.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] While cookies are sent only to the server setting them or a server in the same Internet domain, a web page may contain images or other components stored on servers in other domains.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies that are set during retrieval of these components are called *third-party cookies*.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A third-party cookie, belongs to a domain different from the one shown in the address bar.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This sort of cookie typically appears when web pages feature content from external websites, such as banner advertisements.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This opens up the potential for tracking the user's browsing history and is used by advertisers to serve relevant advertisements to each user.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] As an example, suppose a user visits `www.example.org`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This website contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com`, which, when downloaded, sets a cookie belonging to the advertisement's domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Then, the user visits another website, `www.foo.com`, which also contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com` and sets a cookie belonging to that domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Eventually, both of these cookies will be sent to the advertiser when loading their advertisements or visiting their website.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The advertiser can then use these cookies to build up a browsing history of the user across all the websites that have ads from this advertiser, through the use of the HTTP referer header field.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] As of 2014, some websites were setting cookies readable for over 100 third-party domains.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] On average, a single website was setting 10 cookies, with a maximum number of cookies (first- and third-party) reaching over 800.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The older standards for cookies, RFC 2109 and RFC 2965, recommend that browsers should protect user privacy and not allow sharing of cookies between servers by default.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] However, the newer standard, RFC 6265, explicitly allows user agents to implement whichever third-party cookie policy they wish.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Most modern web browsers contain privacy settings that can block third-party cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Since 2020, Apple Safari, Firefox, and Brave block all third-party cookies by default.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Safari allows embedded sites to use Storage Access API to request permission to set first-party cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In May 2020, Google Chrome 83 introduced new features to block third-party cookies by default in its Incognito mode for private browsing, making blocking optional during normal browsing.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The same update also added an option to block first-party cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In April 2024, Chrome postponed third-party cookie blocking by default to 2025.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In July 2024, Google announced plan to avoid blocking third-party cookies by default and instead prompt users to allow third-party cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The possibility of building a profile of users is a privacy threat, especially when tracking is done across multiple domains using third-party cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, some countries have legislation about cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Website operators who do not disclose third-party cookie use to consumers run the risk of harming consumer trust if cookie use is discovered.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Having clear disclosure (such as in a privacy policy) tends to eliminate any negative effects of such cookie discovery.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The government of the United States set strict rules on setting cookies in 2000 after it was disclosed that the White House drug policy office used cookies to track computer users viewing its online anti-drug advertising.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, privacy activist Daniel Brandt found that the CIA had been leaving persistent cookies on computers that had visited its website.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] When notified it was violating policy, CIA stated that these cookies were not intentionally set and stopped setting them.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] On 25 December 2005, Brandt discovered that the National Security Agency (NSA) had been leaving two persistent cookies on visitors' computers due to a software upgrade.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] After being informed, the NSA immediately disabled the cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, the European Union launched the Directive on Privacy and Electronic Communications (e-Privacy Directive), a policy requiring end users' consent for the placement of cookies, and similar technologies for storing and accessing information on users' equipment.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In particular, Article 5 Paragraph 3 mandates that storing technically unnecessary data on a user's computer can only be done if the user is provided information about how this data is used, and the user is given the possibility of denying this storage operation.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The Directive does not require users to authorise or be provided notice of cookie usage that are functionally required for delivering a service they have requested, for example to retain settings, store log-in sessions, or remember what is in a user's shopping basket.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In 2009, the law was amended by Directive 2009/136/EC, which included a change to Article 5, Paragraph 3.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Instead of having an option for users to opt out of cookie storage, the revised Directive requires consent to be obtained for cookie storage.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The definition of consent is cross-referenced to the definition in European data protection law, firstly the Data Protection Directive 1995 and subsequently the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] As the definition of consent was strengthened in the text of the GDPR, this increased the quality of consent required by those storing and accessing information such as cookies on users devices.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In a case decided under the Data Protection Directive however, the Court of Justice of the European Union later confirmed however that the previous law implied the same strong quality of consent as the current instrument.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In addition to the requirement of consent which stems from storing or accessing information on a user's terminal device, the information in many cookies will be considered personal data under the GDPR alone, and will require a legal basis to process.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This has been the case since the 1995 Data Protection Directive, which used an identical definition of personal data, although the GDPR in interpretative Recital 30 clarifies that cookie identifiers are included.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] While not all data processing under the GDPR requires consent, the characteristics of behavioural advertising mean that it is difficult or impossible to justify under any other ground.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Consent under the combination of the GDPR and e-Privacy Directive has to meet a number of conditions in relation to cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] It must be freely given and unambiguous: preticked boxes were banned under both the Data Protection Directive 1995 and the GDPR (Recital 32).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The GDPR is specific that consent must be as 'easy to withdraw as to give', meaning that a reject-all button must be as easy to access in terms of clicks and visibility as an 'accept all' button.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] It must be specific and informed, meaning that consent relates to particular purposes for the use of this data, and all organisations seeking to use this consent must be specifically named.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The Court of Justice of the European Union has also ruled that consent must be 'efficient and timely', meaning that it must be gained before cookies are laid and data processing begins instead of afterwards.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The industry's response has been largely negative.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Robert Bond of the law firm Speechly Bircham describes the effects as "far-reaching and incredibly onerous" for "all UK companies".
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Simon Davis of Privacy International argues that proper enforcement would "destroy the entire industry".
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] However, scholars note that the onerous nature of cookie pop-ups stems from an attempt to continue to operate a business model through convoluted requests that may be incompatible with the GDPR.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Academic studies and regulators both describe widespread non-compliance with the law.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A study scraping 10,000 UK websites found that only 11.8% of sites adhered to minimal legal requirements, with only 33.4% of websites studied providing a mechanism to reject cookies that was as easy to use as accepting them.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A study of 17,000 websites found that 84% of sites breached this criterion, finding additionally that many laid third party cookies with no notice at all.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A W3C specification called P3P was proposed for servers to communicate their privacy policy to browsers, allowing automatic, user-configurable handling.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] However, few websites implement the specification, and the W3C has discontinued work on the specification.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Third-party cookies can be blocked by most browsers to increase privacy and reduce tracking by advertising and tracking companies without negatively affecting the user's web experience on all sites.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Some sites operate 'cookie walls', which make access to a site conditional on allowing cookies either technically in a browser, through pressing 'accept', or both.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In 2020, the European Data Protection Board, composed of all EU data protection regulators, stated that cookie walls were illegal.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Many advertising operators have an opt-out option to behavioural advertising, with a generic cookie in the browser stopping behavioural advertising.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] However, this is often ineffective against many forms of tracking, such as first-party tracking that is growing in popularity to avoid the impact of browsers blocking third party cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Furthermore, if such a setting is more difficult to place than the acceptance of tracking, it remains in breach of the conditions of the e-Privacy Directive.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Most websites use cookies as the only identifiers for user sessions, because other methods of identifying web users have limitations and vulnerabilities.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] If a website uses cookies as session identifiers, attackers can impersonate users' requests by stealing a full set of victims' cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] From the web server's point of view, a request from an attacker then has the same authentication as the victim's requests; thus the request is performed on behalf of the victim's session.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Listed here are various scenarios of cookie theft and user session hijacking (even without stealing user cookies) that work with websites relying solely on HTTP cookies for user identification.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Traffic on a network can be intercepted and read by computers on the network other than the sender and receiver (particularly over unencrypted open Wi-Fi).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This traffic includes cookies sent on ordinary unencrypted HTTP sessions.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Where network traffic is not encrypted, attackers can therefore read the communications of other users on the network, including HTTP cookies as well as the entire contents of the conversations, for the purpose of a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] An attacker could use intercepted cookies to impersonate a user and perform a malicious task, such as transferring money out of the victim's bank account.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This issue can be resolved by securing the communication between the user's computer and the server by employing Transport Layer Security (HTTPS protocol) to encrypt the connection.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] A server can specify the `Secure` flag while setting a cookie, which will cause the browser to send the cookie only over an encrypted channel, such as a TLS connection.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to cause a DNS server to cache a fabricated DNS entry (called DNS cache poisoning), then this could allow the attacker to gain access to a user's cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For example, an attacker could use DNS cache poisoning to create a fabricated DNS entry of `f12345.www.example.com` that points to the IP address of the attacker's server.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The attacker can then post an image URL from his own server (for example, `http://f12345.www.example.com/img_4_cookie.jpg`).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Victims reading the attacker's message would download this image from `f12345.www.example.com`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Since `f12345.www.example.com` is a sub-domain of `www.example.com`, victims' browsers would submit all `example.com`-related cookies to the attacker's server.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to accomplish this, it is usually the fault of the Internet service providers for not properly securing their DNS servers.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] However, the severity of this attack can be lessened if the target website uses secure cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the attacker would have the extra challenge of obtaining the target website's TLS certificate from a certificate authority, since secure cookies can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Without a matching TLS certificate, victims' browsers would display a warning message about the attacker's invalid certificate, which would help deter users from visiting the attacker's fraudulent website and sending the attacker their cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be stolen using a technique called cross-site scripting.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This occurs when an attacker takes advantage of a website that allows its users to post unfiltered HTML and JavaScript content.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] By posting malicious HTML and JavaScript code, the attacker can cause the victim's web browser to send the victim's cookies to a website the attacker controls.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] When another user clicks on this link, the browser executes the piece of code within the `onclick` attribute, thus replacing the string `document.cookie` with the list of cookies that are accessible from the current page.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] As a result, this list of cookies is sent to the `attacker.com` server.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] If the attacker's malicious posting is on an HTTPS website `https://www.example.com`, secure cookies will also be sent to attacker.com in plain text.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] It is the responsibility of the website developers to filter out such malicious code.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Such attacks can be mitigated by using HttpOnly cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] These cookies will not be accessible by client-side scripting languages like JavaScript, and therefore, the attacker will not be able to gather these cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In older versions of many browsers, there were security holes in the implementation of the XMLHttpRequest API.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This API allows pages to specify a proxy server that would get the reply, and this proxy server is not subject to the same-origin policy.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For example, a victim is reading an attacker's posting on `www.example.com`, and the attacker's script is executed in the victim's browser.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] The script generates a request to `www.example.com` with the proxy server `attacker.com`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Since the request is for `www.example.com`, all `example.com` cookies will be sent along with the request, but routed through the attacker's proxy server.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Hence, the attacker would be able to harvest the victim's cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] This attack would not work with secure cookies, since they can only be transmitted over HTTPS connections, and the HTTPS protocol dictates end-to-end encryption (i.e. the information is encrypted on the user's browser and decrypted on the destination server).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the proxy server would only see the raw, encrypted bytes of the HTTP request.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] For example, Bob might be browsing a chat forum where another user, Mallory, has posted a message.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] If Bob's bank keeps his authentication information in a cookie, and if the cookie hasn't expired, then the attempt by Bob's browser to load the image will submit the withdrawal form with his cookie, thus authorizing a transaction without Bob's approval.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Besides privacy concerns, cookies also have some technical drawbacks.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] In particular, they do not always accurately identify users, they can be used for security attacks, and they are often at odds with the Representational State Transfer (REST) software architectural style.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] If more than one browser is used on a computer, each usually has a separate storage area for cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Hence, cookies do not identify a person, but a combination of a user account, a computer, and a web browser.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Thus, anyone who uses multiple accounts, computers, or browsers has multiple sets of cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p01] Likewise, cookies do not differentiate between multiple users who share the same user account, computer, and browser.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Some of the operations that can be done using cookies can also be done using other mechanisms.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] A JSON Web Token (JWT) is a self-contained packet of information that can be used to store user identity and authenticity information.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] This allows them to be used in place of session cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Unlike cookies, which are automatically attached to each HTTP request by the browser, JWTs must be explicitly attached to each HTTP request by the web application.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] The HTTP protocol includes the basic access authentication and the digest access authentication protocols, which allow access to a web page only when the user has provided the correct username and password.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] If the server requires such credentials for granting access to a web page, the browser requests them from the user and, once obtained, the browser stores and sends them in every subsequent page request.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] This information can be used to track the user.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] The query string part of the URL is the part that is typically used for this purpose, but other parts can be used as well.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] The Java Servlet and PHP session mechanisms both use this method if cookies are not enabled.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] This method consists of the web server appending query strings containing a unique session identifier to all the links inside of a web page.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] When the user follows a link, the browser sends the query string to the server, allowing the server to identify the user and maintain state.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] These kinds of query strings are very similar to cookies in that both contain arbitrary pieces of information chosen by the server and both are sent back to the server on every request.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Since a query string is part of a URL, if that URL is later reused, the same attached piece of information will be sent to the server, which could lead to confusion.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] For example, if the preferences of a user are encoded in the query string of a URL and the user sends this URL to another user by e-mail, those preferences will be used for that other user as well.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Moreover, if the same user accesses the same page multiple times from different sources, there is no guarantee that the same query string will be used each time.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] For example, if a user visits a page by coming from a page *internal to the site* the first time, and then visits the same page by coming from an *external search engine* the second time, the query strings would likely be different.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] If cookies were used in this situation, the cookies would be the same.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Other drawbacks of query strings are related to security.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Storing data that identifies a session in a query string enables session fixation attacks, referer logging attacks and other security exploits.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Transferring session identifiers as HTTP cookies is more secure.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Another form of session tracking is to use web forms with hidden fields.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] This technique is very similar to using URL query strings to hold the information and has many of the same advantages and drawbacks.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] In fact, if the form is handled with the HTTP GET method, then this technique is similar to using URL query strings, since the GET method adds the form fields to the URL as a query string.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] But most forms are handled with HTTP POST, which causes the form information, including the hidden fields, to be sent in the HTTP request body, which is neither part of the URL, nor of a cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] This approach presents two advantages from the point of view of the tracker.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] First, having the tracking information placed in the HTTP request body rather than in the URL means it will not be noticed by the average user.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Second, the session information is not copied when the user copies the URL (to bookmark the page or send it via email, for example).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] All current web browsers can store a fairly large amount of data (2–32 MB) via JavaScript using the DOM property `window.name`.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] This data can be used instead of session cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] The technique can be coupled with JSON/JavaScript objects to store complex sets of session variables on the client side.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] The downside is that every separate window or tab will initially have an empty `window.name` property when opened.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] In some respects, this can be more secure than cookies because its contents are not automatically sent to the server on every request like cookies are, so it is not vulnerable to network cookie sniffing attacks.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Some users may be tracked based on the IP address of the computer requesting the page.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] The server knows the IP address of the computer running the browser (or the proxy, if any is used) and could theoretically link a user's session to this IP address.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] However, IP addresses are generally not a reliable way to track a session or identify a user.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Many computers designed to be used by a single user, such as office PCs or home PCs, are behind a network address translator (NAT).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] This means that several PCs will share a public IP address.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Furthermore, some systems, such as Tor, are designed to retain Internet anonymity, rendering tracking by IP address impractical, impossible, or a security risk.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Because ETags are cached by the browser, and returned with subsequent requests for the same resource, a tracking server can simply repeat any ETag received from the browser to ensure an assigned ETag persists indefinitely (in a similar way to persistent cookies).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Additional caching header fields can also enhance the preservation of ETag data.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] ETags can be flushed in some browsers by clearing the browser cache.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] The browser cache can also be used to store information that can be used to track individual users.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] This technique takes advantage of the fact that the web browser will use resources stored within the cache instead of downloading them from the website when it determines that the cache already has the most up-to-date version of the resource.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] For example, a website could serve a JavaScript file with code that sets a unique identifier for the user (for example, `var userId = 3243242;`).
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] After the user's initial visit, every time the user accesses the page, this file will be loaded from the cache instead of downloaded from the server.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] A browser fingerprint is information collected about a browser's configuration, such as version number, screen resolution, and operating system, for the purpose of identification.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Fingerprints can be used to fully or partially identify individual users or devices even when cookies are turned off.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Basic web browser configuration information has long been collected by web analytics services in an effort to accurately measure real human web traffic and discount various forms of click fraud.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] With the assistance of client-side scripting languages, collection of much more esoteric parameters is possible.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Assimilation of such information into a single string constitutes a device fingerprint.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] In 2010, EFF measured at least 18.1 bits of entropy possible from browser fingerprinting.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Canvas fingerprinting, a more recent technique, claims to add another 5.7 bits.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Some web browsers support persistence mechanisms which allow the page to store the information locally for later use.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] The HTML5 standard (which most modern web browsers support to some extent) includes a JavaScript API called Web storage that allows two types of storage: local storage and session storage.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Local storage behaves similarly to persistent cookies while session storage behaves similarly to session cookies, except that session storage is tied to an individual tab/window's lifetime (AKA a page session), not to a whole browser session like session cookies.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Internet Explorer supports persistent information in the browser's history, in the browser's favorites, in an XML store ("user data"), or directly within a web page saved to disk.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] Some web browser plugins include persistence mechanisms as well.
[src:csrf-protection/http-cookie-p02] For example, Adobe Flash has Local shared object and Microsoft Silverlight has Isolated storage.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] In computing, the **same-origin policy** (**SOP**) is a concept in the web application security model.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Under the policy, a web browser permits scripts contained in a first web page to access data in a second web page, but only if both web pages have the same *origin*.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] An origin is defined as a combination of URI scheme, host name, and port number.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] This policy prevents a malicious script on one page from obtaining access to sensitive data on another web page through that page's Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] This mechanism bears a particular significance for modern web applications that extensively depend on HTTPS cookies to maintain authenticated user sessions, as servers act based on the HTTP cookie information to reveal sensitive information or perform state-changing actions.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] A strict separation between content provided by unrelated sites must be maintained on the client-side to prevent the loss of data confidentiality or integrity.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy applies only to scripts.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] This means that resources such as images, CSS, and dynamically loaded scripts can be accessed across origins via the corresponding HTML tags (with fonts being a notable exception).
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Attacks take advantage of the fact that the same origin policy does not apply to HTML tags.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] There are some mechanisms available to relax the SOP; one of them is cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The concept of same-origin policy was introduced by Netscape Navigator 2.02 in 1995, shortly after the introduction of JavaScript in Netscape 2.0.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] JavaScript enabled scripting on web pages, and in particular programmatic access to the DOM.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The policy was originally designed to protect access to the DOM, but has since been broadened to protect sensitive parts of the global JavaScript object.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] All modern browsers implement some form of the same-origin policy as it is an important security cornerstone.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The algorithm used to calculate the "origin" of a URI is specified in RFC 6454, Section 4.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] For absolute URIs, the origin is the triple {scheme, host, port}.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] If the URI does not use a hierarchical element as a naming authority (see RFC 3986, Section 3.2) or if the URI is not an absolute URI, then a globally unique identifier is used.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Two resources are considered to be of the same origin if and only if all these values are exactly the same.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] To illustrate, the following table gives an overview of typical outcomes for checks against the URL "**http://www.example.com/dir/page.html**".
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Unlike other browsers, Internet Explorer does not include the port in the calculation of the origin, using the Security Zone in its place.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy protects against reusing authenticated sessions across origins.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The following example illustrates a potential security risk that could arise without the same-origin policy.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Assume that a user is visiting a banking website and doesn't log out.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Then, the user goes to another site that has malicious JavaScript code that requests data from the banking site.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Because the user is still logged in on the banking site, the malicious code could do anything the user could do on the banking site.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] For example, it could get a list of the user's last transactions, create a new transaction, etc.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] This is because, in the original spirit of a World Wide Web, browsers are required to tag along authentication details such as session cookies and platform-level kinds of the Authorization request header to the banking site based on the domain of the banking site.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The bank site owners would expect that regular browsers of users visiting the malicious site do not allow the code loaded from the malicious site access the banking session cookie or platform-level authorization.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] While it is true that JavaScript has no direct access to the banking session cookie, it could still send and receive requests to the banking site with the banking site's session cookie.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Same Origin Policy was introduced as a requirement for security-minded browsers to deny read access to responses from across origins, with the assumption that the majority of users choose to use compliant browsers.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Counteracting the abuse of the write permission requires additional CSRF protections by the target sites.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] In some circumstances, the same-origin policy is too restrictive, posing problems for large websites that use multiple subdomains.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] At first, a number of workarounds such as using the fragment identifier or the `window.name` property were used to pass data between documents residing in different domains.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Netscape Navigator briefly contained a taint checking feature.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The feature was experimentally introduced in 1997 as part of Netscape 3.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The feature was turned off by default, but if enabled by a user it would allow websites to attempt to read JavaScript properties of windows and frames belonging to a different domain.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The browser would then ask the user whether to permit the access in question.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] If two windows (or frames) contain scripts that set domain to the same value, the same-origin policy is relaxed for these two windows, and each window can interact with the other.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] For example, cooperating scripts in documents loaded from orders.example.com and catalog.example.com might set their `document.domain` properties to “example.com”, thereby making the documents appear to have the same origin and enabling each document to read properties of the other.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Setting this property implicitly sets the port to null, which most browsers will interpret differently from port 80 or even an unspecified port.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] To assure that access will be allowed by the browser, set the document.domain property of both pages.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The `document.domain` concept was introduced as part of Netscape Navigator 3, released in 1996.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The other technique for relaxing the same-origin policy is standardized under the name cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] This standard extends HTTP with a new `Origin` request header and a new `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] It allows servers to use a header to explicitly list origins that may request a file or to use a wildcard and allow a file to be requested by any site.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Browsers such as Firefox 3.5, Safari 4 and Internet Explorer 10 use this header to allow the cross-origin HTTP requests with XMLHttpRequest that would otherwise have been forbidden by the same-origin policy.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Another technique, cross-document messaging, allows a script from one page to pass textual messages to a script on another page regardless of the script origins.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Calling the postMessage() method on a Window object asynchronously fires an "onmessage" event in that window, triggering any user-defined event handlers.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] A script in one page still cannot directly access methods or variables in the other page, but they can communicate safely through this message-passing technique.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Since HTML `<script>` elements are allowed to retrieve and execute content from other domains, a page can bypass the same-origin policy and receive JSON data from a different domain by loading a resource that returns a JSONP payload.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] JSONP payloads consist of an internal JSON payload wrapped by a pre-defined function call.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] When the script resource is loaded by the browser, the designated callback function will be invoked to process the wrapped JSON payload.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Modern browsers will permit a script to connect to a WebSocket address without applying the same-origin policy.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] However, they recognize when a WebSocket URI is used, and insert an **Origin:** header into the request that indicates the origin of the script requesting the connection.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] To ensure cross-site security, the WebSocket server must verify that that origin is permitted to receive a reply.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The behavior of same-origin checks and related mechanisms is not well-defined in a number of corner cases such as for pseudo-protocols that do not have a clearly defined host name or port associated with their URLs (file:, data:, etc.).
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] This historically caused a fair number of security problems, such as the generally undesirable ability of any locally stored HTML file to access all other files on the disk, or communicate with any site on the Internet.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Lastly, certain types of attacks, such as DNS rebinding or server-side proxies, permit the host name check to be partly subverted, and make it possible for rogue web pages to directly interact with sites through addresses other than their "true", canonical origin.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The impact of such attacks is limited to very specific scenarios, since the browser still believes that it is interacting with the attacker's site, and therefore does not disclose third-party cookies or other sensitive information to the attacker.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Even when same-origin policy is in effect (without being relaxed by Cross-Origin Resource Sharing), certain cross-origin attacks can be performed.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] WebRTC can be used to find out the internal IP address of a victim.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] If attempting to connect to a cross-origin port, responses cannot be read in face of same-origin policy, but a JavaScript can still make inferences on whether the port is open or closed by checking if the onload/onerror event fires, or if we get a timeout.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] This gives opportunities for cross-origin portscanning.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Further, JavaScript snippets can use techniques like cross-site leaks to exploit long-standing information leakages in the browser to infer information cross-origin.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] These attacks can be counteracted by implementing a Cross-Origin Resource Policy (CORP) header, which allows a website owner to block cross-origin or cross-site resources, like images, videos, and stylesheets.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] CORP can also block JavaScript-initiated `fetch` requests, but only if they are sent with the `no-cors` request mode.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy does not prevent the browser from making GET, POST, OPTIONS, and TRACE requests; it only prevents the responses from being read by user code.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Therefore, if an endpoint uses one of these "safe" request methods to write information or perform an action on a user's behalf, it can be exploited by attackers.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Note that the same-origin policy does not apply to cookies for historical reasons.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] If multiple adversarial sites are deployed on the same hostname with different port numbers, contrary to the SOP, all cookies set by any of the sites are shared.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] This can be used to leak users' session tokens and steal account information.
[src:csrf-protection/same-origin-policy] Therefore, web services should be separated by differentiating subdomains rather than port numbers.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] In computer science, a **session identifier**, **session ID** or **session token** is a piece of data that is used in network communications (often over HTTPS) to identify a session, a series of related message exchanges.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] Session identifiers become necessary in cases where the communications infrastructure uses a stateless protocol such as HTTP.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] For example, a buyer who visits a seller's website wants to collect a number of articles in a virtual shopping cart and then finalize the shopping by going to the site's checkout page.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] This typically involves an ongoing communication where several webpages are requested by the client and sent back to them by the server.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] In such a situation, it is vital to keep track of the current state of the shopper's cart, and a session ID is one way to achieve that goal.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] A session ID is typically granted to a visitor on their first visit to a site.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] As session IDs are often used to identify a user that has logged into a website, they can be used by an attacker to hijack the session and obtain potential privileges.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] A session ID is usually a randomly generated string to decrease the probability of obtaining a valid one by means of a brute-force search.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] Many servers perform additional verification of the client, in case the attacker has obtained the session ID.
[src:csrf-protection/session-id] Examples of the names that some programming languages use when naming their cookie include JSESSIONID (Java EE), PHPSESSID (PHP), and ASPSESSIONID (Microsoft ASP).
